\pard\keepn \plain\b\fs28 Character Information\plain\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \fs20 To play Mordor, you must first create a character (your Mordor alter-ego).  Each character requires several basic pieces of information that the game uses in various ways.
\par 
\par The name that you wish to be known by is used whenever another character wishes to refer to you specifically.  For example, when giving gold or items, a name is required.  When healing, your character\'92s name is needed.  \cf2 Choose your name well since it cannot ever be changed again.\plain\fs20   Only one character in the game can have a given name at a time.
\par \pard 
\par The race you choose to be will determine your maximum age, how quickly you learn (gain experience) and how strong, intelligent, wise, healthy, charismatic and dexterous you can be.  There are several other important points concerning your race; they will be discussed later.  The race you choose will also determine the number of \'91stat points\'92 you have when creating your character.  You can discover this by exploring different race selections when creating your character.
\par \pard 
\par \b\cf1 Stats
\par \plain\fs20 There are six basic statistics (stats) that determine how well or poorly your character will do when faced with certain tasks (e.g. fighting, casting spells, etc.).  Some Items and Spells may require a minimum stat to use or cast.  Some guilds may also require a minimum stat to join.  Certain items found in the dungeon may modify a stat while equipped, but the unmodified (natural) stat is still used in some circumstances (i.e. the guilds look only at your natural unmodified stats when deciding if you may join.  Also, the ability to equip or use an item, along with the maximum spell points a character has, is based on a characters natural unmodified stats).  You may raise your natural stats by using certain items you can find in the dungeon.
\par \pard 
\par The six basic statistics (stats) are described as to what effect they have on your characters abilities.
\par \fs24 
\par \pard\fi175 \fs20\cf1 Strength (Str): Your character\'92s Physical Strength determines:\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\li355\fi175 \fs20\cf2 > Your chances of hitting a monster in combat
\par > How much damage is done when you hit a monster\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\fi175 \fs20\cf2 
\par \cf1 Intelligence (Int): Your character\'92s Intelligence determines:\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\li355\fi175 \fs20\cf2 > Your chances of hitting a monster in combat
\par > The maximum spell points that your character is allowed
\par > Your ability to identify an item
\par > Your ability to identify a monster\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\fi175 \fs20\cf2 
\par \cf1 Wisdom (Wis): Your character\'92s common sense and insight. This gives you:\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\li355\fi175 \fs20\cf2 > Your chances of hitting a monster in combat
\par > The maximum spell points your character is allowed
\par > Your ability to recognize a trap on a chest
\par > Your ability to identify an item
\par > Your ability to recognize a monster
\par > Your chances of leaving combat without being hit\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\fi175 \fs20\cf2 
\par \cf1 Constitution (Con): Your character\'92s "healthiness" consists of:\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\li355\fi175 \fs20\cf2 > The number of hits you receive when you make a level
\par > The chance of being raised when dead
\par > Your ability to resist special attacks from monsters:
\par    poison, disease, stoning, aging, paralysis, "breath" (being fire, cold or other
\par    breath types), and spells cast by monsters.\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\fi175 \fs20\cf2 
\par \cf1 Charisma (Cha): Your character\'92s beauty and leadership. It will determine:\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\li355\fi175 \fs20\cf2 > Your chances of having monsters join and become your companions
\par > How long a companion will stay with you
\par > The chance of monsters becoming hostile towards you\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\fi175 \fs20\cf2 
\par \cf1 Dexterity (Dex): Your character\'92s speed and agility determining:\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\li355\fi175 \fs20\cf2 > Your chance of hitting a monster in combat
\par > Your ability to disarm traps
\par > How long it takes your character to open a chest while in combat
\par > The chances a monster has of stealing from you
\par > Your chances of leaving combat without being hit
\par > Your chances of surprising monsters\plain\fs24 
\par \pard \fs20\cf2 
\par \plain\fs20 When a stat has reached its natural peak, it will appear in bold type on the screen.  For example: \b 26\plain\fs20 .
\par 
\par 
\par \b\cf1 Attack/Defense (Att/Def)
\par \plain\fs20 These numbers vary with what items you are wearing, your statistics (strength, etc.), your characters fighting ability and experience level.  Some spells will modify your Att/Def, making your character harder to hit.  The Att/Def of your character is a percentage representation of how well you do in combat.  An Att/Def of 9/12 means that you have an 9% additional chance of hitting a monster while the monster has an additional 12% chance of missing you.  Keep in mind that as your character progresses and as you head deeper into the dungeon, the monsters will be more experienced and have a higher Att/Def.
\par \pard 
\par 
\par \b\cf1 Hits
\par \plain\fs20 Hits determine how much abuse and damage your character can take before dying.  They depend heavily on the level in your strongest guild.  Your constitution is also important in determining your maximum hit points.  You can receive "bonus" hits when you make a level if your constitution is above 16 (and you have not yet reached ML in the current guild you are receiving hits from).  When your character\'92s hits reach 0, you are dead.  You can be raised by another character or in the morgue (discussed later).  Hit points are expressed in a fraction.  For example, 12/12 means that you are at full strength, while 6/12 means you are at half strength.  The first number represents your current hits while the second number represents your maximum hits.  You can raise your hits by achieving higher levels in your guild or having \'91special\'92 events occur.  If you ever see 0/12, you will be dead.  Some guilds have the ability to cast spells (e.g. Healers) and heal lost hits.
\par \pard 
\par 
\par \b\cf1 Experience
\par \plain\fs20 Experience is used to determine how much your character has learned (from fighting, casting spells, opening chests, etc.).  When you have reached a certain amount of experience, your guild will allow you to "make level" which will increase your character\'92s powers.  Both your race and guild will affect how much experience is required to make a level in your current guild.
\par 
\par 
\par \b\cf1 Gold
\par \plain\fs20 Gold in Mordor is practically weightless, so there is no limit as to how much your character can carry.  Gold is what makes the entire city function.  When buying items, making levels in guilds, raising dead characters or companions, you need gold.  It\'92s a good idea to use the bank to store your gold, considering that some monsters have the ability to steal it from you - and sometimes in great amounts.
\par \pard 
\par 
\par \b\cf1 Spell Points & Spell Level
\par \plain\fs20 Every character has a certain number of Spell Points that they can use for casting spells (even if they don't know any).  As a character's Intelligence and Wisdom go up, so do the maximum number of spell points that they have.  Like Hit Points, Spell Points are expressed in a fraction that show the current number of points and maximum number of points.  Every character also has a 'spell level', which is related to a character's \i current\plain\fs20  Guild & Guild Level.  The power of a spell is based on a character's spell level, which goes up as a character raises levels in their guild(s).
\par \pard 
