\pard\keepn \plain\b\fs28 Encounters: Monsters\plain\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \fs20 Rumor has it that the dungeon is more than ten levels deep and contains hundreds of different types of inhabitants.  Since few have ventured beyond the first level, little is known about the creatures that lurk below.  Some are Humanoid and good in nature, some are more Animal and Neutral in nature.  However, some are Demons, foul and evil.  Basically, if one can imagine it, one can probably find it somewhere in the dungeon.
\par 
\par \b\cf1 Lairs
\par \plain\fs20 Some monsters tend to stay in the same place all the time - these locations are known as \'91Lairs\'92.  If you encounter a monster in its lair, you will usually find more goodies as well.  Beware that many monsters that are found only in lairs can be more dangerous than the ones who wander around.  There are also some creatures that will only be found in their lair and nowhere else in the dungeon - because of this, some of these monsters tend to carry unique items.
\par \pard 
\par \b\cf1 Resistances
\par \plain\fs20 Some creatures are rumored to have natural resistances to certain elements and magics while others are said to require powerful and sometimes magical items to defeat.  Unfortunately, the only way to find this out is usually by trial and error.
\par 
\par Below is a collection of known facts about some of the creatures that roam the upper levels.
\par \fs24 
\par \pard\li175 \fs20 Outcast \b\cf1 Goblins & Kobolds
\par \plain\fs20 These little guys are everywhere on the first level.  Small and quick, they\'92re excellent for target practice and make good snacks for giants.  They\'92re not very dangerous except to inexperienced characters.  They quite often give useful Potions and Tomes as well.
\par 
\par \b\cf1 Clean-up
\par \plain\fs20 The acidic nature of these little creatures keep the dungeon floor nice and shiny.  While the Clean-Up is usually docile, they have a habit of attacking anybody or anything that comes around.  These creatures aren\'92t hard to kill, but they can spit acid, which makes them dangerous.
\par \pard\li175 
\par \b\cf1 Dungeon Bear & Giant Owl
\par \plain\fs20 These creatures are the most common Animals on the first level.  To a beginning character, the Dungeon Bear is deadly, but to an experienced character, both of these creatures are good for gaining experience.
\par 
\par \b\cf1 Giant Spider & Giant Centipede
\par \plain\fs20 The insects of the upper levels aren\'92t too dangerous, but can poison a character if they are able to hit them.
\par 
\par \b\cf1 Zombie
\par \plain\fs20 These undead creatures are mean and hard to kill, since they don\'92t really care about much.  Known for giving items that raise stats, these creatures are also good for gaining experience.
\par \pard\li175 
\par \b\cf1 Footpad & Gredlan Rogue
\par \plain\fs20 The thieves of the upper levels, these Humanoids are very good at stealing items from a character, which also means they quite often have stores of treasure and items.
\par \fs24 
\par \pard \fs20 The above information should give a starting player enough knowledge to know what to run away from and what to stay and fight.
\par 
\par As a player becomes more experienced, running into new monsters isn\'92t as threatening since the player may be able to relate the name of the monster in some fashion to previously encountered monsters.  However, a new monster that has a name like no other is completely unknown, and caution should probably be used when fighting such creatures.
\par 
\par Also, it\'92s good for a player to keep track of what type (i.e. humanoid, undead, demon) a monster is (which can generally be guessed by the assigned monster picture).  The reason for this is so a player knows which "charm\'94 spell (i.e. \'91Control Humanoid\'92) may work on a monster.  Also keep in mind that monsters of like types generally share the same abilities (i.e. insects poison, slimes spit acid, etc.).  Quite often, Mages have to go by Trial and Error for charming monsters and getting companions.  \'91Dominate Undead\'92 just doesn\'92t work on a Dragon.
\par \pard 
