\pard\keepn \plain\b\fs28 Items\plain\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \fs20 The term \'91item\'92 refers to any object that your character wears, carries, or can use.  Your character has 40 item \'91slots\'92 where your items are listed.  You can buy items in the store, find them in the dungeon, or exchange them with other characters.
\par 
\par You can learn what an item does in the store by identifying it.  Items can modify any one or more of the following: attack, defense, stats, hits, age, spell points, resistances, swings, and damage done to monsters.  Some items can cast a spell and will show how many \'91charges\'92 or times you can cast that spell listed next to them.  Certain items weigh you down, causing you to drown in water or quicksand and increasing the damage you take when you fall into a pit.
\par \pard 
\par In general, If you wish to use an item, you must \i Equip\plain\fs20  it - however, some items (i.e. Tomes, Rods, Potions, etc.) do not need to be equipped to be \i Used\plain\fs20 .  A weapon must be equipped before you can fight with it.  To cast a spell from an item, you \i Use\plain\fs20  the item.  You can \i Give\plain\fs20  and \i Leave\plain\fs20  (Drop) items also.  An item may require certain minimum stats and may be restricted to certain guilds.
\par 
\par \b Aligned Items\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\li175 \fs20 Quite often, you will find items that are \'91aligned\'92.  This means that only a character of the given alignment can use the item to its fullest potential.  If a Neutral character Equips an item that is aligned Good, the character will only benefit from half of the items abilities.  If a Good character Equips an item that is aligned Evil (and vise versa), the item will attach itself to the character and become cursed - having adverse affects on the character in the process.  Items that are Unaligned (no alignment) can be used by all characters without any problems.  Using (versus Equipping) an item of a different alignment will have no affect, still taking away one \'91charge\'92.
\par \pard\li175 
\par \fs24 
\par \pard \b\fs20 Class Restriction\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\li175 \fs20 Some items will be 'class restricted'.  This means that a characters current guild must be a high enough level in order for the character to equip or use the item.  Some items cannot be used by some guilds (and will not be listed in the item information).  A 'non-class restricted' item is usable by a character who is a member of any guild (and high enough level in that guild) to use the item.  A good example is a level 30 Nomad and a level 1 Mage.  If the character attempts to equip an Iron Dagger (which is not class restricted), they will be allowed to because the level 30 Nomad part of the character can use the item.  However, if the character attempts to equip an item such as Padded Leather Armor, they will not be able to use it (even though their Nomad level it high enough to use it) because it's a 'class restricted' item, and their Mage level is only 1 (which is too low to use the item).  For more information, see the\b  Item Information\plain\fs20 , section of the \uldb Game Screen\plain\fs20  topic.
\par \pard\li175 \fs24 
\par \pard \fs20 
\par \b Item Classes\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\li175 \fs20 Every item is of a certain "class\'94, for example a Bronze Sword is of the "Sword\'94 sub-class, which is a member of the "Weapon\'94 class.  A Dagger is of the "Dagger\'94 sub-class, which is also a member of the "Weapon\'94 class.  So,  Swords, Daggers, Maces, etc. are all members of the Weapons class.  Same with armor sub-classes (i.e. Leather Armor, Chain Armor, etc.), these are all members of the "Armor\'94 class.  Now, a character can only Equip one item of a given class at once - this means that a character cannot use two types of "Armor\'94 or two items in the "Shield\'94 class at once.  Same goes for \i Rings\plain\fs20 , \i Stones\plain\fs20 , etc.  When an item is identified in the store, depending on the ID level, your character will be told what class the item is a member of.  Items such as Potions, Tomes, Dust, etc. cannot be equipped at all, just used.\fs24 
\par \pard \fs20 
\par 
\par \b Metals\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\li175 \fs20 Most of the metal items in the General Store are made from Bronze.  This metal is readily available, making Bronze Items inexpensive.  Any other type of item (i.e. Weapon) made of a stronger is usually found in the dungeon.  Below is a list and brief description of known metals:\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \pard\li175 \fs20\cf1 Bronze
\par \plain\fs20 Many Bronze items are only found in the store - the reason is because they\'92re cheap to make.  A Bronze item does well for a starting character, but as one ventures deeper into the dungeon, it just doesn\'92t cut it.
\par 
\par \cf1 Iron
\par \plain\fs20 Items made from Iron are common in the dungeon and are slightly stronger than Bronze and tend to offer more protection or attack capabilities.
\par 
\par \cf1 Steel
\par \plain\fs20 Much harder than iron, weapons made of steel usually offer quicker and stronger strikes.  The armor from this metal is also more reliable.
\par \pard\li175 
\par \cf1 Adamantite
\par \plain\fs20 Stronger than Steel, items forged from Adamantite offer the protection and swiftness of steel and are generally more durable.\fs24 
\par \pard \fs20 
\par Rumor has it that a metal called Mithril, which is twice as strong as Adamantite, can be found deeper in the dungeon.  However, very few have seen items made from this substance and there is currently no proof that such items can be found anymore.  It was also heard that something even stronger than Mithril was found once, but such a rumor quickly died out.
\par 
\par A character can also find many other items that really don\'92t specify the substance they are made from.  One of them is the \i Lethe Dagger\plain\fs20 , a swift wicked blade constructed by magical iron used by Thieves and Mages.  Another is the \i Brown Cloak\plain\fs20 , which is widely found on Level 1 by starting adventurers.  The best thing to do with any item that a character hasn\'92t seen before is take it to the store and completely identify it so that one knows what advantages the item can offer.,
\par \pard 
\par \b Weapons\plain\fs24 
\par \pard\li175 \fs20 There are many weapons which one can find both in the store and in the depths below.  Some of these weapons will offer more than one swing in combat, allowing the wielding character to strike down more than one foe at a time.  Items that give a character multiple swings will only offer extra swings if a foe is stuck down by a preceding swing.  For example, if a 3 swinged item kills on the first swing, but only damages a creature on the second, a third swing will not be available.  The same rules apply for character who have additional swings from guild abilities.\fs24 
